.vs 11
HBUILD6 allows the Model 4P user to start the system from a hard
disk drive without using a start-up diskette.  This system is 
compatible with LS-DOS 6.3.x operating systems and is
invisible to application packages.

The Model 4 and 4D owner may also use this product if the "C" or "D" ROM is
replaced with the "X" or "XD" ROM which is capable of booting from a hard disk drive.


\s+2Requirements\s-2

HBUILD6 comes configured for one of the following hard disk drivers.  (The
presence of a hard disk controller that works with this driver is assumed.)

.in .5i
.ti .-5i
1.	TRSHD6 (Radio Shack) or RSHARD6 (Misosys) running on a WD 8x300
controller board from Radio Shack with write-protect support, or a 
Western Digital TB-1 controller board (1010/2010).

.ti -.5i
2.	MSCSI6 (Misosys) running on a XEBEC or ADAPTEC controller with a
Misosys host-to-SCSI interface.

.ti -.5i
3.	Powersoft Series RS running on a WD 8x300 controller from Radio
Shack with write-protect support.

.ti -.5i
4.	Powersoft Series I running on a WD100x series controller, port
mapped at 0x7*, with no write-protect support.
.br

.in 0i
HBUILD6 will display and the label on the HBUILD6 diskette indicate
which version you have obtained.

Other disk drivers may also work but cannot be supported at this time.

HBUILD6 requires a LS-DOS 6.3.x logical drive to be on the first physical
drive.   It must also be located on head 1 (ones-based) of the drive.  (This
may not be
the case if there is more than one operating system on your hard
disks.) 
This logical drive must contain the LS-DOS 6.3.x
operating system and currently be defined as logical Drive 0.
If you are using a hard disk driver that allows logical drives to start
on cylinders
other than 0, you must make sure that logical Drive 0 begins on cylinder 0.

If your operating system has patches to support an XLR8er adapter or a
Anitek extended memory adapter, the installation will not work without
removing these patches first.  These patches add code to the
low memory driver area, and HBUILD6 must utilize this area during the
boot process.  Included on this disk is an utility to dynamically apply the
XLR8er patches after the system boots.  To remove the patches that would
interfere with HBUILD6, use the command BACKUP SYS0:s :0 (S,I)
where :s is the logical number of a floppy containing an unpatched copy
of LS-DOS.

If you used the Radio Shack HARDGEN utility to initialize the hard disks
and included the operating system on the hard disk, your system should
be ready to be converted.

If you did not install the operating system on the hard disk, you
can convert one of the data drives to a system drive, or
reinitialize the system. (See "Converting a Data drive to a
System drive" for more information.)  If you decide to reinitialize the
drives, be sure to save all of your files before starting
the process.


\s+2Installing the Hard Disk Boot Track\s-2

.in .5i
.ti -.5i
1.	Start your system with the hard disk start-up diskette as you normally do.

.ti -.5i
2.	At the LS-DOS Ready prompt, remove the start-up diskette
from floppy Drive 0.

.ti -.5i
3.	Insert the \fBHard Disk Boot Initialization\fR diskette into Drive 0
and close the drive door.

.ti -.5i
4.	Make sure the write-protect light is off (if present) on the primary
hard disk drive. 

.ti -.5i
5.	Type:
	\fLHBUILD6 \fR 
.bx "ENTER"
.br

.ti -.5i
6.	After several seconds, HBUILD6 displays:

		\fLHard Disk Boot Track Installed Successfully\fR

(If HBUILD6 does not display this message, it displays an
error message.  See "Error Messages" for information
on how you should proceed.)

.ti -.5i
7.	If there were no errors, remove the diskette from Drive 0.

.ti -.5i
8.	Press RESET.  After a few seconds the system should prompt
for the date, time or display the LS-DOS Ready prompt.  Note that the
boot screen now appears all at once.  This is normal.
.br

.in 0i
Your hard disk boot installation is complete.  Store the 
\fBHard Disk Boot Initialization\fR
diskette in a safe place.  You will need this diskette if you ever reformat
your hard disks or upgrade the operating system.  To install a new operating
system or reformat your hard disks you will need to repeat this procedure to
restore the hard disk boot capability.


